"2011-03-19 12:46:03","2011-03-19 12:46:03","<div class=\"mceTemp\"><dl id=\"attachment_153\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\" style=\"width: 310px;\"><dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-153\" title=\"2.2\" src=\"http://www.nethaat.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/2.2-300x194.jpg\" alt=\"Handblock printing floral motifs\" width=\"300\" height=\"194\" /></dt><dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Handblock printing floral motifs</dd></dl>Block printing is a fabric design technique that is believed to have evolved in the 3<sup>rd</sup> century in China. Later, the technique also found its way to India,Europe and other places across the world. Wooden blocks were the most commonly used implements to make these designs although some craftsmen also used porcelain or metal blocks. Block printing is a highly labour intensive task and requires meticulous care from the craftsman. But once completed, the fabric gains an elegance and splendour that is rarely matched by another design form.INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("153","1","2011-03-19 12:43:08","2011-03-19 12:43:08","","2.2","Handblock printing floral motifs","inherit","open","open","","2-2","","","2011-03-19 12:43:08","2011-03-19 12:43:08","","152","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/2.2.jpg","0","attachment","image/jpeg","0");
INSERT INTO wp_posts VALUES("154","1","2011-03-19 12:44:40","2011-03-19 12:44:40","<div class=\"mceTemp\"><dl id=\"attachment_153\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\" style=\"width: 310px;\"><dt class=\"wp-caption-dt\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-153\" title=\"2.2\" src=\"http://www.nethaat.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/2.2-300x194.jpg\" alt=\"Handblock printing floral motifs\" width=\"300\" height=\"194\" /></dt><dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Handblock printing floral motifs</dd></dl>Block printing is a fabric design technique that is believed to have evolved in the 3<sup>rd</sup> century in China. Later, the technique also found its way to India,Europe and other places across the world. Wooden blocks were the most commonly used implements to make these designs although some craftsmen also used porcelain or metal blocks. Block printing is a highly labour intensive task and requires meticulous care from the craftsman. But once completed, the fabric gains an elegance and splendour that is rarely matched by another design form.</div>\n \n\nIn India, hand block printing from Rajasthan has been very popular and mostly named by the prints and motif styles  as sanganeri  and bagru prints named after the towns in Rajasthan where they originated. The technique of hand block is finding popularity on various forms of cloths like Cotton, silks, georgette etc and is being used in various innovative ways in fashion circuit.\n\nThe Sanganeri hand block printed textile products from Rajasthan have been awarded Geographical Indication (GI) Status that will protect it from being duplicated anywhere else. This status allows some 300 producers of the sanganer region to take legal action against the infringement of the name of their product. The screen printed textiles in Rajasthan which are sold in the name of sanganeri will now be illegal\n\nAlthough hand block printing was very common in olden days before machines made designing so simple and fast; in recent past, not many of these fabric prints were to be found in the fashion circles. However, this printing form seems to be making a spectacular comeback if the recent Fashion Weeks are any measure of current trends.\n\n<strong>Hand block printing in the fashion world</strong>\n\nWell known designer Ritu Kumar gets the credit for revitalising hand block printing and for bringing back interest to this age old fabric art form. Kumar started small with a vision to bring Indias best to the world stage. She had a couple of hand block printers in a small fabric design studio in Calcutta when she first made her entry into the world of fashion design about 30 years back. Today, both Ritu Kumar and hand block printing have carved a niche for themselves in Indian and international fashion.\n\nThe recent display of hand block printed saris and suits by Chaitali Biplab at the Blenders Price Bangalore Fashion Week showed that there are many others who are willing to hold the flame of Indian fabric hand block printing aloft. The back to basics trend that is sweeping through the fashion world is, no doubt, contributing to the impetus that traditional fabric design forms are now beginning to enjoy.\n\n<strong>The appeal of these fabrics</strong>\n\nSubtle shades of colour, traditional materials like crisp cottons, stunning silks or even jute embellished with intricate block printed designs make a stunning formal or casual ensemble. Designers are increasingly using this potent combination to create apparel that is ideally suited for the Indian climate as well as the Indian complexion.\n\nOne thing is very clear from all of this. Hand block printing will never go out of date or seem out of place in any setting, be it a corporate event or a typical Indian glitzy wedding complete with all the pomp and glitter.","Hand Block Printed Fabrics Making a Come Back in Fashion Circuits","","inherit","open","open","","152-revision","","","2011-03-19 12:44:40","2011-03-19 12:44:40","","152","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/?p=154","0","revision","","0");
