\n\n[gallery]\n\n A lot of people have old shoes lying around. They are a bit boring and old fashioned and are rarely used. We are reluctant to throw them to avoid being wasteful, but in the end they are just old shoes piling up in our house.\n\n \n\nDo you have a pair of old shoes?\n\nDo you want to glam up your shoes?\n\nDo you want to give them a new birth?\n\n \n\nIf you just said \'yes\', then here we go-\n\nWith the following tips and tricks you can convert your old, granny shoes into glam shoes instantly. Or you can make previously unsuitable shoes match your new outfit. Or you can make one pair of shoes seem like several. From beautiful to fashionable, elaborating your shoes can be easy with the following simple ways.\n\nThe first step of your artsy mission is to acquire the ingredients. You just need some clip findings, ribbons, beads, lace, faux pearls, silk or paper flowers, clip on shoe accessories, rhinestones, cabochons and other tiny trinkets and don\'t forget contact cement and bobby pins to secure these things on your shoes.\n\nAfter you gather all bits and bytes you can, make your designs. Keep your designs simple. Just don\'t paste all stuff on one pair of shoes. Try to make different design with different color combinations for different pairs. However, you can have the same design for both the shoes of the same pair.\n\nThere are many ways to design simple tidbits. You can make a tailored bow (actually a pair would be better) from ribbons or you can give a romantic touch by affixing lace, a strand of faux pearls or delicate beaded trim around the opening of sandals. You can use studded rhinestones to attach the lace to add glitzy touch. You can also give a spring look to your sandals by affixing silk or paper flowers or butterflies and sea shells and more.\n\nEvery design doesnt have to be elegant. You can decorate as casually as you want. You can also use fabric paint designs on your shoes. Design making needs a lot of practice and once you are on you\'ll become better and better with time. Once you\'ve had a little practice you\'ll have the most extensive shoe wardrobe of anyone you know.\n\nWith this level of creativity your shoes can transform into customized, engaging compliments to your personality. You can also turn a pair of cheap pumps or flats into refined accessories for you ensembles, so you should learn to decorate your plain shoes to get the great look you desire. The next time you\'re considering a new pair of shoes thinks instead of redecorating a pair you already own and impress your friends with your creativity.","Getting creative with your old shoes","","publish","open","open","","getting-creative-with-your-old-shoes","","","2011-02-20 14:41:13","2011-02-20 14:41:13","","0","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/?p=103","0","post","","0");
\n\nKundan is one of the oldest methods of traditional jewelry making in India dating back to the Mughal era. Kundan is pure gold and Meena is the process of enameling. Kundan Meena jewelry pieces have encrusted gemstones on one side and smooth decorated colored surfaces on the other. This kind of jewelry making involves setting a precious stone such as a diamond, sapphire or ruby on its mount using a gold foil.\n\nMost of the intricate Kundan Meena jewelry is made by skilled artisans, which adds to the value of the pieces. The designs are simple yet aesthetic, consisting of simple geometric patterns to more elaborate embellishments. One standout feature of most Kundan Meena jewelry pieces is that they are colorful and eye-catching. Regardless of whether a precious or semi-precious gem is used, the finished product looks beautiful and sophisticated.\n\n<strong>How Kundan Meena jewelry is made</strong>\n\nThe process of Kundan Meena jewelry making first involves preparing the gold foil. The gold is made soft and malleable after passing it through a rolling machine that churns out flat sheets of 22 carat. The resulting gold sheet is hammered and beaten to get the required thickness.\n\nAfter the soft gold sheet is ready, the artisans carve the desired gold design with their hands or using tweezers. The resulting pattern forms the outer walls of the finished jewelry piece. The number of designs that have to be carved out depend on the type and size of the piece under making. After the gold designs have been fashioned out of the gold foil, they are bonded or soldered together to form the final shape of the jewelry piece. The soldering is done traditionally by puffing fire out of pipes onto the gold pieces and combining them into one solid piece, such as an earring or a necklace.\n\nThe black residue on the jewelry piece after the soldering process is cleaned using mild chemicals and then dried. After this, the piece is handed over to the gem setter. In gem setting, first the lac is heated and poured into the creek, which is supposed to hold the gem. Meanwhile the gem or stone that has to be encrusted is prepared. A gold or silver foil is fixed to the back of the gem to make it gleam. The gemstones are now placed into the creeks or holders.\n\nIn the final step, the bits of 24 carat gold foils or kundan are set into the sides of the gemstones till they grip on tightly. In the Meenakari process, which is intricate and laborious, enamel colors are added to the jewelry piece through an engraving and fusing technique.\n\nEvery Indian bride dreams of wearing a one-of-a-kind Kundan Meena jewelry set these days. After exquisite Kundan Meena pieces worn by Aishwarya Rai in the Bollywood epic Jodha Akbar caught the publics fancy, many jewelry showrooms in India have seen a rise in sales of Kundan Meena jewelry. Traditional handcrafted jewelry such as Kundan Meena has been cherished for centuries in India and is now finding popularity world over.","Making of Kundan Meena Jewelry","This writeup tells in details about one of the very popular and traditional jewelry art in India","inherit","open","open","","52-revision-16","","","2011-01-28 13:40:37","2011-01-28 13:40:37","","52","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/?p=70","0","revision","","0");
\n\nEven as the global demand for Indian handicrafts is on the rise, the industry here is caught in the midst of a dilemma. The increasing number of orders is good news indeed, especially coming after a bad recessive year, when the buyers for handmade Indian crafts significantly dropped. But a serious dearth of skilled workers is threatening the industrys growth prospects. The shortage of skilled artisans is not a sudden event as the numbers have steadily been dwindling over the past years. There are many reasons why the children of artisans and the younger generation craftsmen are turning away from these traditional crafts:\n\n <strong>Lack of consistent demand</strong>\n\n This industry, by its very nature, is fickle where the demand is concerned. The demand is predominantly seasonal with Christmas time bringing in almost unmanageable bulk orders while the period beyond that is almost dry. Young artisans find this massively fluctuating demand unnerving and feel that they cannot depend on this unpredictable industry for their livelihood.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_73\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"300\" caption=\"Artisan at work\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-73\" title=\"Artisans  \" src=\"http://www.nethaat.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Artisans-Pic-2-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Artisan at work\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />[/caption]\n\n<strong>Absence of guaranteed earnings</strong>\n\nDue to the fluctuating demand, it is very difficult for Indian artisans involved in traditional arts and crafts to earn a steady income all through the year. In comparison, a government job or employment in the organized sector ensures a guaranteed monthly salary. As artisan families are rarely affluent enough to get by without earnings from the sale of their handmade wares, the lure of an assured paycheck month on month is naturally enticing.\n\n <strong>Lack of access to buyers</strong>\n\nThe Indian handicrafts market is highly disorganized. Only a handful of the more enterprising craftsmen have links with the right dealers and government showrooms. This allows them to reap the benefits of proper marketing and organized sales. For the others lost in the by-lanes of the massive country, reaching buyers is a tough task in itself. International tourists only visit known repositories of traditional wares like advertised showrooms and government sponsored exhibitions for their purchases. Craftsmen practicing their trades without such backing remain undiscovered.\n\n <strong>Lack of regulation</strong>\n\n In the absence of strong government regulation of the handicrafts market, traditional artisans get only a fraction of what their pieces actually sell for in the global markets. Although many efforts are on to bring these master craftspeople to the market directly, the changes have not permeated to all levels of this industry. Unless all craftsmen get fair pricing and have steady demand throughout the year, keeping the tradition alive is going to be a difficult task.\n\n The waning interest among the next generation of craftsmen in taking up their ancestral trade is evident at shows and exhibitions. One can see that nearly all stalls at such events are manned by elderly artisans, well past the age of retirement in business parlance. The youngsters are not keen on working long, hard hours for meager and unpredictable earnings. There is no answer yet to the one question, that haunts the thoughts of these master craftsmen: Who will keep my art alive after I am gone?. It can only be hoped that some timely intervention will save the exquisite Indian crafts from waning away.\n\nNote:This is an article  by the nethaat team and no part of it can be copied/reproduced without permission","Indian Artisans - A Dying Workforce","","publish","open","open","","indian-artisans-a-dying-workforce","","","2011-02-01 14:59:23","2011-02-01 14:59:23","","0","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/?p=71","0","post","","1");
